</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62B19B82FFB6FFFA69F7F89BFE72FE2A" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="2A14C809FFB6FFFA69F7F89BFE72FE2A" blockId="6.[151,1437,1868,2039]" lastBlockId="7.[151,1437,151,1185]" lastPageId="7" lastPageNumber="8" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB6FFFB69F7F89BFEF5F89D" bold="true" box="[151,274,1868,1894]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Recognized among other tingid genera by a combination of the following characters: body rhomboid; maximum width across hemelytra wider than maximum width across paranota; head shorter than its maximum width across compound eyes, with five spines; antennal segments I close to each other at their bases; bucculae contiguous with each other at anterior ends; rostrum reaching posterior margin of mesosternum; pronotum convex in anterior part, tricarinate; lateral margin of pronotum not emarginate in anterior part; hood semi-globose, higher than pronotal disc at highest part; pronotal carinae carinate; paranotum reflexed, expanding inward, without longitudinal ridge, bulged upward in posterior part, forming a dome opening inward; outer margin of paranotum resting on pronotal disc at anterior and posterior ends; posterior process well-developed; anterior margin of hemelytron strongly curved outward; costal area distinct; subcostal area subhorizontal; discoidal area flat; Cu (cubital) and R+M (radiomedial) veins carinate; hypocostal lamina with a single row of areolae in its entire length; ostiolar peritreme well-developed; metasternum wider than mesosternum; metasternal laminae separated from each other at posterior ends; abdominal sternites IV–VIII in male and IV–VII in female each with a transverse furrow throughout their width; pygophore elevated at center of venter; ovipositor with well-developed ovivalvula at base; and paratergite IX in female unilobed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62B19B82FFB7FFFA69A7FE0CFBFDFBCE" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="2A14C809FFB7FFFA69A7FE0CFBF9FDE1" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA69A7FE0CFEDCFE0E" bold="true" box="[199,315,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6823FE0CFE28FE0F" authority="Souma &amp; Ishikawa, 2022" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2022" box="[323,463,475,500]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Limnostatua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6823FE0CFE28FE0F" box="[323,463,475,500]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Limnostatua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA68B7FE0CFDA5FE0E" bold="true" box="[471,578,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="03ECA960FFB7FFFA68B7FE0CFDA5FE0E" box="[471,578,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
comprises a single species, namely 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6ABEFE0CFB3EFE0E" authority="(Scott, 1880)" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Scott" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[990,1241,475,501]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Limnostatua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lewisi" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6ABEFE0CFBDAFE0E" box="[990,1085,475,501]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">L. lewisi</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4E3AB5F8FFB7FFFA6D2EFE0CFB36FE0E" author="Scott, J." box="[1102,1233,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="305 - 317" refId="ref40313" refString="Scott, J. (1880) On a collection of Hemiptera from Japan. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1880, 305 - 317. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1880. tb 02032. x" type="journal article" year="1880">Scott, 1880</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6D82FE0CFA84FE0E" bold="true" box="[1250,1379,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="03ECA960FFB7FFFA6D82FE0CFA84FE0E" box="[1250,1379,475,501]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, distributed in 
<collectingCountry id="52BC8899FFB7FFFA6872FE28FEB2FDE2" box="[274,341,511,537]" name="Japan" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Japan</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="52BC8899FFB7FFFA6800FE28FE41FDE2" box="[352,422,511,537]" name="China" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">China</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry id="52BC8899FFB7FFFA6880FE28FDC3FDE2" box="[480,548,511,537]" name="South Korea" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Korea</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation id="4E3AB5F8FFB7FFFA6B53FE28FD57FDE2" author="Scott, J." box="[563,688,511,537]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="305 - 317" refId="ref40313" refString="Scott, J. (1880) On a collection of Hemiptera from Japan. Transactions of the Entomological Society of London, 1880, 305 - 317. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1365 - 2311.1880. tb 02032. x" type="journal article" year="1880">Scott 1880</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4E3AB5F8FFB7FFFA6BDCFE28FC7FFDE2" author="Drake, C. J. &amp; Maa, T. C." box="[700,920,510,537]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="87 - 101" refId="ref36242" refString="Drake, C. J. &amp; Maa, T. C. (1953) Chinese and other Oriental Tingoidea (Hemiptera). Quarternary Journal of Taiwan Museum, 6 (2), 87 - 101." type="journal article" year="1953">Drake &amp; Maa 1953</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="4E3AB5F8FFB7FFFA6AC4FE28FBF6FDE1" author="Lee, C. E." box="[932,1041,511,538]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" pagination="91 - 111" refId="ref38587" refString="Lee, C. E. (1967) Tingidae from Korea (Heteroptera). Mushi, 41, 91 - 111." type="journal article" year="1967">Lee 1967</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A14C809FFB7FFFA69A7FDF4FD92FCA6" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA69A7FDF4FEB4FDC7" authority="Souma &amp; Ishikawa, 2022" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2022" box="[199,339,547,572]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Limnostatua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA69A7FDF4FEB4FDC7" box="[199,339,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Limnostatua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA683DFDF4FE2DFDC6" bold="true" box="[349,458,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="03ECA960FFB7FFFA683DFDF4FE2DFDC6" box="[349,458,547,573]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6BC7FDF4FCFEFDC6" authorityName="Drake" authorityYear="1953" box="[679,793,547,573]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Hurdchila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6BC7FDF4FCFEFDC6" box="[679,793,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Hurdchila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, with 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6A07FDF4FB1DFDC5" authority="(Drake &amp; Poor, 1936)" baseAuthorityName="Drake &amp; Poor" baseAuthorityYear="1936" box="[871,1274,547,574]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Hurdchila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="togularis">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6A07FDF4FC9CFDC7" box="[871,891,547,572]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6AECFDF4FC16FDC6" box="[908,1009,547,573]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">togularis</emphasis>
(Drake &amp; Poor, 1936)
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="B290D48CFFB7FFFA6C6CFDF4FA73FDC6" box="[1292,1428,547,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 20" captionStartId="33.[151,250,960,984]" captionTargetBox="[155,1436,452,936]" captionTargetId="figure-137@33.[151,1436,452,936]" captionTargetPageId="33" captionText="FIGURE 20. Habitus images of Hurdchila togularis from Thailand. Dried specimen, dorsal and lateral views (A, B). Ventral structures: rostrum (C), male terminalia (D) and female terminalia (E). Scale bars: A, B, 1.0 mm; C–E, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6610027" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6610027/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 20A–E</figureCitation>
) as the 
<typeStatus id="F51076ABFFB7FFFA6983FD90FEF4FD9A" box="[227,275,583,609]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">type</typeStatus>
species, in general appearance, but can be distinguished by the following characteristics: hood semiglobose; pronotal carinae carinate (
<figureCitation id="B290D48CFFB7FFFA6B47FDBCFD43FD7E" box="[551,676,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,673,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-248@8.[151,1437,669,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitus images of Limnostatua lewisi comb. nov. from Japan. Dried specimen, dorsal, dorsolateral and lateral views (A–C). Ventral structures: rostrum (D), male terminalia (E) and female terminalia (F). Scale bars: A–C, 1.0 mm; D–F, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6609977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6609977/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4A–C</figureCitation>
); median carina of pronotum lower than hood at maximum height; paranotum forming a dome opening inward; outer margin of paranotum resting on pronotal disc at anterior and posterior ends; subcostal area of hemelytron subhorizontal; and metasternum wider than mesosternum (
<figureCitation id="B290D48CFFB7FFFA6C78FD64FA95FD36" box="[1304,1394,691,717]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,673,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-248@8.[151,1437,669,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitus images of Limnostatua lewisi comb. nov. from Japan. Dried specimen, dorsal, dorsolateral and lateral views (A–C). Ventral structures: rostrum (D), male terminalia (E) and female terminalia (F). Scale bars: A–C, 1.0 mm; D–F, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6609977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6609977/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). In contrast, 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA699FFD00FE96FD0A" authorityName="Drake" authorityYear="1953" box="[255,369,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Hurdchila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA699FFD00FE96FD0A" box="[255,369,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Hurdchila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
presents the following characteristics: hood semi-ellipsoid; pronotal carinae rounded; median carina of pronotum as high as or higher than hood at maximum height; paranotum forming a cyst closed inward; outer margin of paranotum not resting on pronotal disc in its entire length; subcostal area of hemelytron subvertical; and metasternum as wide as mesosternum.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="2A14C809FFB7FFFA69A7FCB0FBFDFBCE" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA69A7FCB0FEB4FC7B" authority="Souma &amp; Ishikawa, 2022" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2022" box="[199,339,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Limnostatua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA69A7FCB0FEB4FC7B" box="[199,339,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Limnostatua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA683DFCB0FE2EFC7A" bold="true" box="[349,457,871,897]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="03ECA960FFB7FFFA683DFCB0FE2EFC7A" box="[349,457,871,897]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
resembles 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6B2DFCB0FD36FC7A" authorityName="Stal" authorityYear="1873" box="[589,721,871,897]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Cysteochila" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6B2DFCB0FD36FC7A" box="[589,721,871,897]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Cysteochila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in the shape of pronotal carinae, but it differs from the latter genus in the followint characters: lateral margin of pronotum not emarginate in anterior part; hood semi-globose (
<figureCitation id="B290D48CFFB7FFFA69C0FC78FEFCFC32" box="[160,283,943,969]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="8.[151,250,1854,1878]" captionTargetBox="[151,1437,673,1831]" captionTargetId="figure-248@8.[151,1437,669,1831]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURE 4. Habitus images of Limnostatua lewisi comb. nov. from Japan. Dried specimen, dorsal, dorsolateral and lateral views (A–C). Ventral structures: rostrum (D), male terminalia (E) and female terminalia (F). Scale bars: A–C, 1.0 mm; D–F, 0.2 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6609977" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6609977/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Fig. 4A–C</figureCitation>
), higher than pronotal disc at highest part; paranotum bulged upward in posterior part, forming a dome opening inward; outer margin of paranotum resting on pronotal disc at anterior and posterior ends; and metasternal laminae separated from each other at posterior ends. 
<taxonomicName id="EDABB38AFFB7FFFA6B98FC20FC63FBEB" authority="Souma &amp; Ishikawa, 2022" authorityName="Souma &amp; Ishikawa" authorityYear="2022" box="[760,900,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Tingidae" genus="Limnostatua" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus" status="gen. nov.">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6B98FC20FC63FBEB" box="[760,900,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Limnostatua</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6AEDFC20FC1FFBEA" bold="true" box="[909,1016,1015,1041]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="03ECA960FFB7FFFA6AEDFC20FC1FFBEA" box="[909,1016,1015,1041]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" rank="genus">gen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be distinguished from the allied genera by the remarkable and unique shape of the pronotum as described above.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="62B19B82FFB7FFFA69A7FBE8FE7EFB5A" pageId="7" pageNumber="8" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="2A14C809FFB7FFFA69A7FBE8FE7EFB5A" blockId="7.[151,1437,151,1185]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA69A7FBE8FEA9FBA2" bold="true" box="[199,334,1087,1113]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is formed from the Latin noun 
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6A1DFBE8FC5CFBA2" box="[893,955,1087,1113]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">limne</emphasis>
, meaning pond, and the Latin noun 
<emphasis id="18DF141BFFB7FFFA6C31FBE8FA72FBA3" box="[1361,1429,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">statua</emphasis>
, meaning statue, referring to the habitat and the scraggy stature of the 
<typeStatus id="F51076ABFFB7FFFA6ACCFBB4FC3BFB86" box="[940,988,1123,1149]" pageId="7" pageNumber="8">type</typeStatus>
species of the genus designated below; the gender is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
